#MEM id=rules source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Technical/dev/skills/design-and-build/vercel-composition-patterns/rules/architecture-compound-components.md
M|rules|title: Use Compound Components
M|rules|impact: HIGH
M|rules|impactDescription: enables flexible composition without prop drilling
M|rules|tags: composition, compound-components, architecture
M|rules|Structure complex components as compound components with a shared ctx. Each
M|rules|subcomponent accesses shared state via ctx, not props. Consumers compose the
M|rules|pieces they need.
M|rules|**Incorrect (monolithic component with render props):**
M|rules|```tsx
M|rules|function Composer({
M|rules|renderHeader,
M|rules|renderFooter,
M|rules|renderActions,
M|rules|showAttachments,
M|rules|showFormatting,
M|rules|showEmojis,
M|rules|}: Props) {
M|rules|return (
M|rules|<form>
M|rules|{renderHeader?.()}
M|rules|<Input />
M|rules|{showAttachments && <Attachments />}
M|rules|{renderFooter ? (
M|rules|renderFooter()
M|rules|) : (
M|rules|<Footer>
M|rules|{showFormatting && <Formatting />}
M|rules|{showEmojis && <Emojis />}
M|rules|{renderActions?.()}
M|rules|</Footer>
M|rules|)}
M|rules|</form>
M|rules|)
M|rules|}
M|rules|```
M|rules|**Correct (compound components with shared ctx):**
M|rules|```tsx
M|rules|const ComposerContext = createContext<ComposerContextValue | null>(null)
M|rules|function ComposerProvider({ children, state, actions, meta }: ProviderProps) {
M|rules|return (
M|rules|<ComposerContext value={{ state, actions, meta }}>
M|rules|{children}
M|rules|</ComposerContext>
M|rules|)
M|rules|}
M|rules|function ComposerFrame({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
M|rules|return <form>{children}</form>
M|rules|}
M|rules|function ComposerInput() {
M|rules|const {
M|rules|state,
M|rules|actions: { update },
M|rules|meta: { inputRef },
M|rules|} = use(ComposerContext)
M|rules|return (
M|rules|<TextInput
M|rules|ref={inputRef}
M|rules|value={state.input}
M|rules|onChangeText={(text) => update((s) => ({ ...s, input: text }))}
M|rules|/>
M|rules|)
M|rules|}
M|rules|function ComposerSubmit() {
M|rules|const {
M|rules|actions: { submit },
M|rules|} = use(ComposerContext)
M|rules|return <Button onPress={submit}>Send</Button>
M|rules|}
M|rules|// Export as compound component
M|rules|const Composer = {
M|rules|Provider: ComposerProvider,
M|rules|Frame: ComposerFrame,
M|rules|Input: ComposerInput,
M|rules|Submit: ComposerSubmit,
M|rules|Header: ComposerHeader,
M|rules|Footer: ComposerFooter,
M|rules|Attachments: ComposerAttachments,
M|rules|Formatting: ComposerFormatting,
M|rules|Emojis: ComposerEmojis,
M|rules|}
M|rules|```
M|rules|**Usage:**
M|rules|```tsx
M|rules|<Composer.Provider state={state} actions={actions} meta={meta}>
M|rules|<Composer.Frame>
M|rules|<Composer.Header />
M|rules|<Composer.Input />
M|rules|<Composer.Footer>
M|rules|<Composer.Formatting />
M|rules|<Composer.Submit />
M|rules|</Composer.Footer>
M|rules|</Composer.Frame>
M|rules|</Composer.Provider>
M|rules|```
M|rules|Consumers explicitly compose exactly what they need. No hidden conditionals. And the state, actions and meta are dependency-injected by a parent provider, allowing multiple usages of the same componen